segments.text: Vice President of the University of Texas at Dallas by Brenda Nolte on May 3, 1990.
This is being recorded over the phone concerning the feminist movement.
In interest of accumulating knowledge, I'm asking you to donate this tape to me or to the tape or to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
That's fine.
Okay.
What's the date and place of your birth?
July 27, 1941, in Ranger, Texas.
Who was a big influence to you as a child, right at the moment?
Yes, several of them.
Both of my grandmothers, I think, were important in my life.
I had an aunt that was...
10 years older than I am and 10 years younger than my mother.
And she was the first college graduate on that side of the field and was the student leader at Baylor and was an airline stewardess for American Airlines in like 1964 or something like that.
And so she never married and was an independent
And I had a high school home economics teacher that encouraged me to look at leadership positions.
And my mother always pushed me to do things, although some of them were quite traditional.
She always wanted me to have opportunities.
And then I was a great reader of biographies.
I worked in the library as a child.
And I read the Bob Holmes series.
What degrees did you receive in undergraduate and graduate school?
Well, I have a very disjointed educational path, which may be untrue.

We were encouraged to do these very traditional type degrees, and I have three undergraduate degrees, one in economics, one in art education, and one in applied art, and I have a minor in science, and I have a master's in art education, and a master's in liberal arts, and a doctorate in administration.
Why did you receive a doctorate degree?
Where?
Yeah, why and where?
What was the purpose of it?
I got it because my other degree didn't allow me to do the things I wanted to do.
And so I either had a choice of getting an MBA.
I had taken a lot of research courses, seminars, and done a lot of leadership training.
What was life like for a woman at the time you were in college?
College college?
Well, we had a 10 o'clock curfew.
I was the one who called the board and said, this is the board for Hope and Dean, and this is my boyfriend.
To whom I am now married to.
Started going with my sophomore high school.
You did not wear pants and flats.
You didn't wear dressings.
You were not encouraged to use your shoes.
Well, there were a lot of classes in the girls' class.
were not able to be admitted to the college.
My daughter Renee is a man in Texas A&M.
It was even questionable for girls to take life drawing and art life.
It was very late.
It was fairly...
restrictive and a lot of girls started college with the idea that their goal was really to get married, not necessarily to get married.
And particularly I think in the South, in the small towns, that was kind of the norm rather than the exception.
And many, most of my high school
What type of organizations were you part of concerning the women's issue?
In college?
For both, for college and then later on.
There weren't any in college, particularly, although I held a high school.
I was a state officer and teacher, homeowner for the man, which I think was very good because he was trained to do home economics, was the only school in Texas Tech that had a CMLD.
And so there were good role models in CMA, although very traditional.
And I didn't get active in CMA.

As far as the formal organization, I joined the National Organization for Women, but I joined the local organization called Women for Change, and out of that group grew the Women's Center of Dallas, and I served as president of that organization in 1979-1976.
That group was tailored to me

the deeds of feminists in Dallas and started things like the Great Crisis and later it was raised the issue of violence in the family and started things later on there in training with the police during the Dallas Women's Credit Union.
Took on a lot of those kinds of things
I've worked closely with the Planned Parenthood on a lot of issues that women were raising.
And when I was on that panel, Equal Access to Education, and there was an act called the Title IX, an amendment to the Education Act of 1972, and I worked actively to get that
legislation aid passed and then implemented not only in Dallas but across the country.
Did you involved in the Women's National Convention in Houston in 1977?
Yes.
As a matter of fact, I attended.
I didn't have a leadership role then.
It was fascinating.
About six of us piled in a car in Dallas and drove to that convention.
It was very interesting.
Gloria Steinem came about that same year to Dallas, and we hosted her as the women's center.
I had a private thing, a couple of private things for her.
And the Women's Composing Committee, which now celebrates its 25th year, was a catalyst for many of these kinds of activities here in Dallas.
What was the atmosphere like at the convention?
Exciting.
Yeah.
Very upbeat, all new, kind of scary because rumors were that the Ku Klux Klan was going to pick it, and sure enough they did, but not any huge numbers.
It was really fun, and it was my first political conference.
What's your view on EPA and should it be passed?
EPA or ERA?
Oh, sorry, ERA.
I'm sorry, ERA.
EPA is environmental protection.
Sorry about that, ERA.
Well, I don't know.

shame that we still are not legally part of the Constitution as we should have had in Texas, as a matter of fact, because I think the fourth state in the union has ERAs in them, and that is one of the reasons that gave legal emphasis to Roseburg and the Way growing up in Texas.
Women have always been
very independent.
They had to be survived, just to move with, which is one of the reasons I always had a great admire of my grandmother's face.
In very traditional roles, were very independent women, out of possession.
They say, the place they birthed the babies, they grew the food, they built the homes.
Really, women were
or the basics to reason the frontier was settled and civilized.
So it took quite a long time.
The ERA passed in Texas, and there is a state ERA, still in Texas, which has given the company some legal, legal address, ways to address problems.
How do you feel about the abortion issue?
that no one should tell a woman what to do, what happens with her own body, and that everybody should have a right to decide whether or not they are prepared for those responsibilities here.
And if reporting is last resort or anything,
What were the general feelings of women after Roe v. Wade?
Were they surprised that it passed through the Supreme Court?
I think it's the time.
we had think that that finally the country was working quite enough it was part of the whole heady era of the time that the right to be in central was raised.
I think they had think that was part of the whole country coming of age.
It was more of a shock that that right should be placed.
Do you feel like in the 70s that women had equal opportunity in the classroom as well as in sports?
Had it improved since the time you were in high school?
No, it hadn't changed very much at all.
I think with the advent of Title IX, there's been a lot of progress.
When I started teaching students in Dallas in the early 60s and 80s, lots of places were not available, shop places.
I think a lot of the old-time teachers are not prepared for the whole issue of women's administration and should women be involved in it?
Would men work for women?
Would women be really good in the college and kind of manage the school and all those work issues?
were dealt with in a relatively short time period.
Title IX began in the mid-1930s in St. Mary, Ravensburg.
In a five or six year period, I think there were some dramatic changes as far as girls back then.
Have men liberated as quickly in this country as women?
Do you think they're catching up now, or was there a big battle against?
Well, I think in many cases backlash, and they are accepting, I think, the changes quickly because of the economic reality.
Some of them have working lives.
Very few families have survived today, you know, income.
But women, unfortunately, still have two primary jobs.
They're outside of the country.
I think statistics show, over and over, studies show that men are on nearly the same number of hours of work as women.
I think there seems to be a change among younger men.
Has the general view towards women changed?
Is it liberated?
An example would be Sports Illustrated's some suit issue, the popularity of, oh,
The old theory of consciousness, the fact that women still are judged in this much older look than anything else, and the fact that many women who are highly susceptible, married,
And I think it's because economically, it goes back to economically, merchants depend on what they have there on the street.
When the wife gets into a position where she has an opportunity to move to fix her career, the old norm often comes back into play.
That's where the rubber
A lot of jobs where a number of women have taken over the job in some ways is not impressive to us.
It's not a real job.
Now that the children of the movement are in their 20s, what needs to be achieved?
To continue my children and the children of the women's night, the women who were active in the movement, their children are going to have to become adults.
The progress of the night is very fragile with the sub-churches who were in birth.

that women are not included in the Constitution, that abortion rights is a matter that can be overturned by the death of one more justice on the Supreme Court, that America is a very small island in the world of stereotypical gender roles.
The children of women my age have got to realize
and not take all of their rights as an individual for granted in their lives.
It's very fragile that it could be reversed, that they're going to have to revisit and revise some of these battles because they're all shaky.
The walls are shaky and they couldn't have done it unless there is

So, in that reason, I'm very delighted to see that you are examining the issues and talking about the reasons why the protection came down, some of the solutions that have worked for the last two years, where the cracks are and what the reasons are.
Oh, yes.
You're going to have to do a lot of education of young people your age.
Sometimes.
Well, and young women too.
I think it's been very easy for young women to take for granted some of the privileges that have been handed down without understanding the history.
Just for the last question, what are some of your favorite books?
I'm glad we get to retake this because I thought of maybe one of the first, The Feminine Supreme, which was the story of my life and very revealing to me.
The book Her Story, which is
The Handmaid's Tale, which I think is a pseudo-time fiction of what can happen.
And all of the elements of the Handmaid's Tale are in society right now.
It is not that far back to that time.
That if we are not digital, we are not digital.
I think there's magazines that have been post-war.
At the same time, you can't just have a feminist base.
You need to have a good, sound, solid education.
That's what I would change about my life.
I would have gotten a Ph.D. in feminism.
I would have focused my intellectual inquiry earlier.
I wished that I had higher educational opportunities when I got into college.

When I started college, I was told by my husband's counselor that I should not go to college, that I wasn't smart enough to finish, and that the best I should hope for is to marry a rich young man and become a housewife.
My husband, who was my husband,
Second thing I do is go to college and get a good degree and sign up for a contract and delay getting married until the end.
The guidance I had not received along the way.
It had to happen by hook or crook, and I was not...
I was a very traditional girl, and I was married to a sweetheart.
And so I was not a rebel.
without a cause when I was young.
I was a rebel with a cause when I was better.
And now, again, I'm very, very respectful.
Not the medical husband.
Well, I look respectful.
I'm 50, though.
OK.
